<br>
But Bush rubs me up the wrong way, and he has that effect on a lot of Europeans, (he's not terribly charming is he?  What I admire about many truly great leaders is how they win hearts without arousing resentment, he seems pretty devoid of that gift.)<br>
<br>
And why are so many ppl angry about the war? Because undoubtedly life for most ppl in Iraq is now much worse than it would otherwise have been.  Ppl are dying (unnecessarily) and the situation is terrible and it is going to be for a long time. (All of which was predicted by people who simply wanted the weapons inspectors to be given more time. A lot of ppl over here feel they were hustled into this fight much too quickly.)<br>
<br>
No quick victory, no mass uprising against Saddam, no bunkers full of weapons of mass destruction, and precious little honour. (I'm sorry but yes.  Two days ago 2 British soldiers were killed in Iraq. Their families were told by high ranking military officers that they had died honorably in combat. Hours later goes Tony Blair goes on television standing next to George Bush and tells the world that the men were &quot;executed&quot;.  The families are outraged and demand to know why Blair is lying, but they are largely ignored and within hours the attention of the news teams have moved on to the latest batch of civilian casualties in Baghdad.)<br>
<br>
Many of the young soldiers out there now have never known combat before.  They have never known war before.  Neither have i or any of you. That's why it's so easy to sit at home at the PC, unbombed, and rant in favour of it.<br>
<br>
And before anyone starts biting my head off let me stress that I am not anti-war (i want it done and over as quickly as possible) i am not anti-american (a little self-doubt never did anyone any harm) and i believe in reason above all else (so don't flame me if you love that monster truck crashing show on TV - j/k!)<br>
